    • Field Detail

      • grid

        protected ICellable[][] grid
        Two dimensional array of ICellable objects that represents the game board - each ICellable object is a square.

      • moveCounter

        protected int moveCounter
        integer that keeps up with the number of moves that the algorithm made

      • countToWin

        protected int countToWin
        integer for the number of squares in winning line for this game. In order to win, a player needs to have his/her symbols positioned in this number of adjacent squares. For example, if countToWin is 3 then in order to win, a player needs to position 3 squares in a row (vertical, horizontal, or diagonal row). If countToWin is 4, then there needs to be 4 squares occupied by the player in line in order to win.

      • listWinCells

        protected java.util.ArrayList<ICellable> listWinCells
        ArrayList of ICllable objects with the winning squares. The array list of ICellable objects can be used to highlight winning cells on the grid to demonstrate to the user the winning combination.

      • random

        protected java.util.Random random
        Random object to be used to calculate the probability of a perfect move. It is used to simulate game difficulty.

      • perfectMoveProbability

        protected double perfectMoveProbability
        double value from 0 to 1 of perfect move probability. It is calculated based on the game difficulty level and the number of squares on the board. perfectMoveProbability is then used to determine if the move made by the computer needs to be perfect (the best possible move) or random.

    • Method Detail

      • isGameOver

        public boolean isGameOver()
        isGameOver() is a boolean method that tells if the game is over. The game can be over because user won, computer won, or it is a tie (empty squares are available)).
        Returns:
        true if the game is over. Returns false if the game is not over.

      • getWinningCells

        public java.util.ArrayList<ICellable> getWinningCells()
        getWinningCells() method returns the array list of ICellable objects that can be used to highlight winning cells on the grid to demonstrate to the user the winning combination.
        Returns:
        array list of ICellable objects - the cells that make up the winning cells.

      • RegisterMove

        public void RegisterMove(ICellable cell,
                         int ownerId)
        RegisterMove() registers the move - a newly occupied square. When user selects a square and places her/his symbol in the square it needs to be registered with the algorithm so that it can provide the next move made by computer. RegisterMove() method needs to be invoked every time user makes a move.
        Parameters:
        cell - - object that implements ICellable interface
        ownerId - - the player id of the user whose move needs to be registered.

      • checkWinner

        public boolean checkWinner(int playerId)
        checkWinner() is a boolean method that returns true of the requested player won; returns false if requested player have not won;
        Parameters:
        playerId - - integer 'player ID' to check if this player has won the game.
        Returns:
        true if the player with the provided id is the winner; returns false if the player has not won.

      • outputGrid

        public void outputGrid()
        outputGrid() method print the grid using System.out.print to show what Algorithm object has: what squares belong to what players. zero indicates empty cell; other integers indicated the owners of the cells.

      • getNumberToWin

        public int getNumberToWin()
        getNumberToWin() method is a getter that returns the number of squares in winning line. In order to win, a player needs to have his/her symbols positioned in this number of adjacent squares. For example, if getNumberToWin() returns 3 then in order to win, a player needs to position 3 squares in a row (vertical, horizontal, or diagonal row). If getNumberToWin() return 4, then there needs to be 4 squares occupied by the player in line in order to win.
        Returns:
        integer
